Juvenile snowshoe hare sizes: exploratory report

By: Daija Odom

2021-11-10

1. Overview

This report provides an exploratory overview of counts and differences in juvenile snowshoe hare (Lepus americanus) sizes in the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest from 1999 - 2012. Counts were taken from 3 sampling sites (Bonanza Riparian, Bonanza Mature, and Lowland Black Spruce). Specifically, juvenile hare weights are compared by sex and site. And the relationship changes in respect to hind foot length are explored.

2. Data and methods

Snowshoe hare capture-recapture was conducted at 5 locales in the Tanana valley and made available by Associate Professor Knut Kielland and colleagues at the Bonanza Creek Long Term Ecological Research (LTER) Network site (Kielland et al. 2017). Following exploratory data visualization, hare weight between male and female juvenile hares are by unpaired two-sample t-tests using a significance level of (\(\alpha\)) of 0.05 throughout. Differences between groups are described by Cohen’s d effect size and the relationship between hind foot length and hare weight is explored by simple linear regression. All analyses are in R version 4.1.1 using RStudio version 1.4.1717.

3. Preliminary results

A. Number of juvenile hare trappings comparison

Figure 1. Total number of juvenile snowshoe hare trappings (male and female) annually.

The minimum number of juvenile hares trapped are 2 and the maximum number of juvenile hares trapped are 126. The mean annual number of hares trapped is 31.5 and the median is 18.5. Hare counts are highest in 1999 and overall decrease in the years thereafter with the smallest count being in 2010. To standardize the juvenile hare population in future analyses I suggest monitoring vegetation and predators in each site which affect changes in the hare densities and setting up the traps on the same days every year.

B. Juvenile hare weights comparison

Between the sites there is not significant variation in male and female weight.

Figure 3. Hare weight observations (g) for juvenile female and male snowshoe hares. Violet-red (female), sky blue (male), and gray (NA) points indicate individual observations for juvenile hare weights (grams). Data: Kielland et al. (2017).

C. Juvenile weight comparison(male and female snowshoe hares)

Table 1. Descriptive Statistics (mean (g), standard deviation (g), and sample size) of juvenile hare weight. Data: Kielland et al. (2017).
Sex Mean (g) Standard Deviation (g) Sample Size
Female 855.39 292.25 200
Male 945.86 333.22 163
NA 614.55 357.59 15

There is an actual difference of 90.47 (g) in means. Mean hare weights for female juvenile snowshoe hares (855.39 g \(\pm\) 292.25 g, n = 200) were only slightly smaller than those of male juvenile snowshoe hares (945.86 \(\pm\) 333.22 cm, n = 163), a difference of just over 10% (values are mean \(\pm\) 1 standard deviation; t(325.02) = 2.71, p = 0.007). The effect size was small (Cohen’s d = 0.2904674)
